If the minds are agitated in the minority, it is no better within the dem majority. The proposal on the electoral symbol >has provoked malumori also among members of the secretariat Pd like Peppe Provenzano and Marco Sarracino. But also Andrea Orlando crooked his nose with respect to the idea of entering the name of the secretary in the logo. And the former Labour Minister was the protagonist of a position that sounds a warning to Nazareno. Shortly before the vote in Brussels on the <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-04-23/new-patto-stabilita-ue-come-function-26142343/"> new Stability Pact</a>, Orlando had pointed out to journalists: "I hope that our group in Strasbourg will firmly reject the proposal for reform of the Stability Pact. A different vote would result in a negative judgement on the negotiating insipience of our government and on the betrayal that the EU Council has made with respect to the excellent Commission proposal, carried out thanks to the valuable work of Paolo Gentiloni". Words that are beaten with the line followed by the Pd delegation in Europe, <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-04-23/partiti-italiani-astenuti-patto-stabilita-ue-26144384/"> astenutasi dal ballo</a> per non 'rompere' con i resto del Pse, on one hand. And not to give the impression of wanting to defeat the work of Paolo Gentiloni, on the other.
&nbsp;
Done that yesterday, just a few hours from the vote, Orlando returns on the theme: "Gentiloni had made a proposal for reform of the Stability Pact which the EU Council amended and which initially reflected the spirit of the Next Generation and the challenges facing Europe," says Orlando. "A series of interventions from countries like France and Germany have reduced the instruments that Europe will have in the coming years." The result, for Orlando, is a "Stabilita Pact" that conflicts with a higher European ambition and with national interest, a quite paradoxical fact for a government that had to go to Europe to beat the fists on the table and ponder better conditions". A rejection for the government, then. And, of course, not a caress for the outgoing group in Brussels and for the secretary who blessed the path of abstention, after having harshly criticized the Covenant and the government for not having countered it sufficiently: "We will go against this compromise at the bottom," was in fact the line explicit by Schlein on March 5, a few hours from the free way of the European Council to the reform of the Covenant.

