AGI - "Radio me too" is in the storm. The Rai programme ended in the view of the political polemic because this morning, in the opening of its connection to the broadcasts, Senator Ester Mieli> felt asked by the conductor Giorgio Zanchini> if he was Jewish. "A request - say the members of the Brothers of Italy in the Commission of Vigilance on the Rai - that, in addition to bringing back to mind lugubri memories, is unacceptable and intolerable species at a time such as this pervaded by an increasingly rampant anti-Semitism, fed within the Universita' from extremists of left towards which we still await words of condemnation from the left and in particular of the Pd and Elly Schlein. To my colleague, Mieli, we renew our solidarity, and we hope that these words will be followed by those of all other political forces." &nbsp;
"I find really serious and disturbing what happened this morning to the senator of Brothers of Italy Ester Mieli, host of a radio program of the Rai - commented > the president of the Senate, Ignazio La Russo >-. For weeks there have been demonstrations of intolerance to Israel and the Jews throughout Italy and a question like that put by the host is totally unacceptable." "The opinion of a person cannot in any way be linked to the professed religion. To his friend Ester Mieli and the Jewish community - he concluded Russian - comes my sincere solidarity and affectionate closeness". &nbsp;
<br> "On behalf of the whole supervisory committee, unanimous, I express full solidarity to Senator Ester Mieli for what happened this morning in a radio broadcast of the Rai - explained the president of the Supervisory Board Rai Barbara Floridia >-. Feeling to ask a direct question about your religious faith is a violation of the most intimate sphere, made even more serious by the journalist's intention to connect the opinion of the colleague to his religious belief." &nbsp;
<h2>Zanchini: "I'm going to pass through antisemite"</h2>
Is he mortified? "I am. I apologize to FdI's senator, Ester Mieli, but to pass me for an anti-Semite I don't deserve it. It's unfair, incorrect. I lived four years at the house of Jews, I was sent, embedded, with the Israeli army. I'm a friend of Israel. I'll stay and always be." So the conductor of 'Radio Anch'io', Giorgio Zanchini, interviewed by 'Il Foglio', after the episode of this morning.<br> "No, the question did not want to be offensive. He added. And Senator Mieli sent to say that "I express solidarity, that my intention was opposite, that I did not want to hurt her. Everything else."
&nbsp;"I wanted to make it clear that hostile climate breathe Jews - the journalist explained - I asked Professor Driessen if he was Jewish and the same question I asked the senator. I did it just to make the climate clear. If you listen to the transmission you understand. I'm terrified now by asking a congressman whether he's Catholic or not. They want me hanging. I was wrong, but I didn't want to denigrate someone." Don't you think you raised your voice, exaggerated after the question? "I felt overwhelmed by Senator Mieli in seconds. I apologized. I repeat, my intention was opposite. I already called the Israeli embassy. My aunt's husband died, by heart attack, after racial laws. If there's one near Israel, that's me," said Zanchini.
&nbsp;
Solidarity with the senator also came from the Action Leader, Carlo Calenda:> "I find it insensitive, illogical and unacceptable that to express one's opinion it is necessary to clarify one's belief."
For the deputy of Italia Viva&nbsp; Maria Elena Boschi>, vice-president of the Rai Supervisory Committee,&nbsp; "a parliamentary of the Republic judges the protests in the universities' and in the squares on the basis of politics and law, nothing has to do with the religion it professes. Therefore, the journalist's request to express his confession before commenting on the facts of these days."
&nbsp;
"This morning, at the meeting of the Rai Supervisory Commission, I expressed full closeness and solidarity to Senator Ester&nbsp;Mieli, on behalf of my staff and on behalf of the entire Democratic Party group, for what happened this morning in a radio broadcast Rai - said in a note > Senator Francesco Verducci, >member of the Rai Supervisory Commission -. Cataloging a person according to his religious belief is something dangerous and unacceptable to any person and any religious belief. In the climate that we live, of continuous stigmatization that nourishes prejudice, disinformation and discrimination, it is essential to have a language of respect, that it is not and does not appear contingent. That is why we asked the Supervisory Commission to carry out a work session on inclusive and non-discriminatory language, which is so much more important in the election campaigns."

